---
// src/pages/hitl.astro
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import NavBlock from "../components/NavBlock.astro";

const demoSetupCommand = `export HITL_GATE_URL="https://gate.quirgs.com"
export HITL_GATE_TOKEN="<write-token>"`;

const ownSetupCommand = `export HITL_GATE_URL="https://your-hitl-gate.example.workers.dev"
export HITL_GATE_TOKEN="<your-write-token>"`;

const step1Command = `curl -s -X POST $HITL_GATE_URL/events \\
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $HITL_GATE_TOKEN" \\
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \\
  -d '{
    "type": "hitl-test",
    "payload": {
      "item": "my first gate test",
      "stage": "testing",
      "status": "pending"
    }
  }'`;

const step2Command = `curl -s $HITL_GATE_URL/events/<event-id> \\
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $HITL_GATE_TOKEN"`;

const step3Command = `curl -s -X PATCH $HITL_GATE_URL/events/<event-id> \\
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $HITL_GATE_TOKEN" \\
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \\
  -d '{"status": "approved"}'`;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="HITL Gate | Quirgs"
  description="The Quirgs Human-in-the-Loop Gate — an approval queue that sits between an AI agent and any action it isn't allowed to take on its own."
  terminalPath="~/hitl"
>
  <NavBlock currentPath="/hitl/" />

  <div class="line">
    <span class="prompt">admin@quirgs</span><span class="path">~/hitl</span
    ><span class="text-bright">$</span>&nbsp;cat hitl.md
  </div>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <div class="detail-header">
    <h1 class="text-bright">HITL Gate</h1>
    <p class="tagline">
      An approval queue that sits between an AI agent and any action it isn't
      allowed to take on its own.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-bright">WHAT IT IS</h2>
  <p>
    When an AI produces output that requires human sign-off — a compliance
    classification, a risk assessment, a document ready to publish — it posts a
    request to the gate. A human reviews the pending request and approves or
    rejects. The AI proceeds only on approval. Every decision is timestamped and
    stored.
  </p>
  <p>That's your audit trail.</p>
  <p>
    EU AI Act Article 14. NIST AI RMF MANAGE 1.2. ISO 42001 §9.1.<br />
    All require demonstrable human oversight. The gate makes it demonstrable.
  </p>
  <p>
    Think of it as a pull request review — but for AI decisions instead of code.
  </p>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <h2 class="text-bright">WHO IT'S FOR</h2>
  <p>
    Teams that have AI making decisions and need a record that a human reviewed
    and approved those decisions — without relying on Slack messages or email
    threads.
  </p>
  <div class="line">
    &rarr; AI governance leads running compliance workflows
  </div>
  <div class="line">
    &rarr; Engineers wiring oversight into agent-based products
  </div>
  <div class="line">
    &rarr; Anyone who has been told they need documented human oversight of AI
    outputs
  </div>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <h2 class="text-bright">HOW IT WORKS</h2>
  <p>Three operations. One Worker. No SDK required.</p>
  <pre><code>  POST   /events      — AI posts a pending approval request
  GET    /events      — reviewer lists the pending queue
  GET    /events/:id  — reviewer checks the event status
  PATCH  /events/:id  — reviewer approves or rejects</code></pre>
  <p>
    A shared demonstration Worker is live at:<br />
    <a
      href="https://gate.quirgs.com"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener">https://gate.quirgs.com</a
    >
  </p>
  <p>
    Use it to run the 90-second test below. For any real workflow, run your own
    copy of the Worker and point <code>HITL_GATE_URL</code> at it — see
    <a href="#run-your-own">RUN YOUR OWN GATE</a>. Your events never touch Quirgs
    infrastructure.
  </p>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <h2 class="text-bright">PREREQUISITES</h2>
  <p>
    To prevent unauthorized access, the gate Worker requires Bearer token
    authentication for every operation — reads (GET) as well as writes (POST and
    PATCH). The event payloads are not world-readable. To run the test against
    the shared demonstration Worker, request a token:
  </p>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>
  <div>Request a demo token &rarr; <a href="/support/">/support/</a></div>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>
  <p>
    Every example below reads two environment variables —
    <code>HITL_GATE_URL</code> (the gate endpoint) and
    <code>HITL_GATE_TOKEN</code> (your write token). The gate endpoint is never
    hard-coded; it is whatever you point <code>HITL_GATE_URL</code> at. Set the
    pair once and the commands — and the <code>hitl-compliance-gate</code> skill,
    which reads the same two variables — all target the same gate. Point them at
    the shared demo Worker to take the test, or at your own deployment for real
    work.
  </p>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>
  <div class="line">
    <span class="text-bright">Set your environment (demo Worker)</span>
    <button class="copy-btn" data-copy={demoSetupCommand}>Copy</button>
  </div>
  <pre><code>{demoSetupCommand}</code></pre>
  <div class="line">
    Replace 'write-token' with the token you received.
  </div>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <h2 class="text-bright">90-SECOND TEST</h2>
  <p>Run these three commands to fire a live event through the gate.</p>

  <div class="archive-note hitl-note">
    <span class="text-red">[WARNING]&nbsp;</span> The HITL Gate Worker is a shared
    demonstration queue. Do NOT submit production data, credentials, PII (personally
    identifiable information), or sensitive information during testing.
  </div>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <div class="line">
    <span class="text-bright">Step 1 — POST a pending event</span>
    <button class="copy-btn" data-copy={step1Command}>Copy</button>
  </div>
  <pre><code>{step1Command}</code></pre>
  <div class="line">
    &rarr; Returns: <code>{'{"ok":true,"id":"<event-id>"}'}</code>
  </div>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <div class="line">
    <span class="text-bright">Step 2 — Verify the event is pending</span>
    <button class="copy-btn" data-copy={step2Command}>Copy</button>
  </div>
  <pre><code>{step2Command}</code></pre>
  <div class="line">
    &rarr; Returns: <code
      >{'{"id":"...","status":"pending","created_at":...}'}</code
    >
  </div>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <div class="line">
    <span class="text-bright">Step 3 — Approve it</span>
    <button class="copy-btn" data-copy={step3Command}>Copy</button>
  </div>
  <pre><code>{step3Command}</code></pre>
  <div class="line">&rarr; Returns: <code>{'{"ok":true}'}</code></div>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <h2 id="run-your-own" class="text-bright">RUN YOUR OWN GATE</h2>
  <p>
    The shared Worker above is a demonstration queue. Its data store is public to
    anyone holding a token — do not put production, customer, or PII-bearing
    events through it. For real work, run your own copy. The Worker is open
    source: it is a single D1-backed Cloudflare Worker with no external
    dependencies.
  </p>
  <div class="line">1. Clone the Worker source from <code>workers/hitl-gate</code></div>
  <div class="line">
    2. Create a D1 database and bind it as <code>HITL_DB</code> in
    <code>wrangler.toml</code>
  </div>
  <div class="line">3. Set a write token secret and <code>wrangler deploy</code></div>
  <div class="line">
    4. Point <code>HITL_GATE_URL</code> at your own
    <code>*.workers.dev</code> (or custom) hostname
  </div>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>
  <div class="line">
    <span class="text-bright">Set your environment (your Worker)</span>
    <button class="copy-btn" data-copy={ownSetupCommand}>Copy</button>
  </div>
  <pre><code>{ownSetupCommand}</code></pre>
  <p>
    Because the skill and the commands both read <code>HITL_GATE_URL</code>, this
    is the only change required — nothing else points at Quirgs. Every event
    your agents post stays inside your own Cloudflare account.
  </p>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <h2 id="wire-it-to-an-agent" class="text-bright">WIRE IT TO AN AGENT</h2>
  <p>
    Any agent that can run bash or make HTTP requests can use the gate. The
    pattern is always the same:
  </p>
  <div class="line">1. Agent produces output requiring human review</div>
  <div class="line">2. Agent POSTs event &rarr; receives event ID</div>
  <div class="line">3. Agent surfaces event ID to user and waits</div>
  <div class="line">4. Human reviews, PATCHes to approved or rejected</div>
  <div class="line">5. Human tells agent the outcome</div>
  <div class="line">6. Agent proceeds on approved, stops on rejected</div>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>
  <p>
    The hitl-compliance-gate Quirgs skill implements this pattern out of the
    box. Install it and any compliance workflow you run through it is
    automatically gated.
  </p>
  <pre><code>  /plugin install hitl-compliance-gate@quirgs</code></pre>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <h2 class="text-bright">FURTHER READING</h2>
  <div>
    &rarr; <a
      href="/skills/hitl-compliance-gate/"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener">hitl-compliance-gate skill</a
    >
    — compliance gate details
  </div>
  <div>
    &rarr; <a
      href="https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX:32024R1689"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener">EU AI Act Article 14</a
    > — human oversight requirements
  </div>
  <div>
    &rarr; <a
      href="https://www.nist.gov/itl/ai-risk-management-framework"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener">NIST AI RMF MANAGE 1.2</a
    > — risk response and human oversight
  </div>

  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>
  <div class="line">
    <span class="prompt">admin@quirgs</span><span class="path">~/hitl</span
    ><span class="text-bright">$&nbsp;</span><span class="cursor"></span>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .hitl-note {
    border-left-color: var(--accent-red);
    background: rgba(248, 113, 113, 0.03);
  }

  /* The "Returns:" JSON responses are long, unbreakable inline <code> strings
     inside a flex .line. Flex items default to min-width:auto and refuse to
     shrink below their content, so on narrow screens they overflow the
     viewport. Let them shrink and wrap. */
  .line code {
    min-width: 0;
    overflow-wrap: anywhere;
    word-break: break-word;
  }
</style>
